{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca172392-0b3e-4bef-9c3e-fa88287d4417","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap file I/O behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling `File.*` / `Directory.*` directly. In tests, substitute a mock or in-memory implementation.\n\n**Even easier:** use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with a real implementation and a test helper (`MockFileSystem`):\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```\n\n```csharp\n// Production\npublic class MyService(IFileSystem fs)\n{\n    public string Load(string path) => fs.File.ReadAllText(path);\n}\n\n// Test\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>\n{\n    { \"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{ }\") }\n});\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nAssert.Equal(\"{ }\", svc.Load(\"/data/config.json\"));\n```\n\nThis avoids touching the real disk in tests and makes behavior fully controllable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"09f612c7-ff23-4825-b406-7292b929926d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nThe standard approach is to introduce an abstraction (interface) over file system operations and use dependency injection. There's also the well-known `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package that provides this out of the box.\n\nLet me give a concise answer since this is an advice question, not a task to perform on the codebase.","outputTokens":464,"requestId":"0BC3:3A1531:521835:5F6A6A:69F01344"},"id":"ba6d6a24-3ff3-47f6-89ee-b4c8dbc0b7d1","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:54:23.450Z","parentId":"f545caf8-3a38-48c1-a76f-7a66fcd6a5cf"}
